# Solving the `filter_upwards` Problem in Lean 4

We need to prove that if the sets $\{x | p x\}$, $\{x | p' x\}$, $\{x | q x\}$, and $\{x | q' x\}$ are all in the neighborhood filter $\mathcal{N}_x$, then the set $\{x | p x \wedge q x \vee p' x \wedge q' x\}$ is also in $\mathcal{N}_x$.

This is a straightforward application of the filter axioms. Specifically, we can use the fact that a filter is closed under finite intersections and unions. Let's think about how to construct the proof.

First, we need to show that $\{x | p x \wedge q x\}$ is in $\mathcal{N}_x$. This is the intersection of $\{x | p x\}$ and $\{x | q x\}$. Since both of these sets are in $\mathcal{N}_x$, their intersection is also in $\mathcal{N}_x$ by the filter property.

Next, we need to show that $\{x | p' x \wedge q' x\}$ is in $\mathcal{N}_x$. Similarly, this is the intersection of $\{x | p' x\}$ and $\{x | q' x\}$, which is also in $\mathcal{N}_x$.

Finally, we need to show that the union of these two sets is in $\mathcal{N}_x$. The set $\{x | p x \wedge q x \vee p' x \wedge q' x\}$ is the union of $\{x | p x \wedge q x\}$ and $\{x | p' x \wedge q' x\}$. Since both of these sets are in $\mathcal{N}_x$, their union is also in $\mathcal{N}_x$.

