If $A = \{x | p x\}$ and $B = \{x | q x\}$, both in $\mathcal{N}_x$, then $A \cap B \in \mathcal{N}_x$. This is a standard property of filters: the intersection of two sets in the filter is also in the filter.

Similarly, $\{x | p' x\} \cap \{x | q' x\} \in \mathcal{N}_x$.

Then, taking the union of two sets that are in $\mathcal{N}_x$, we get a set that is also in $\mathcal{N}_x$. This is another standard property of filters: the union of sets in the filter is also in the filter.

