/-
`filter_upwards [h‚āĀ, ‚čĮ, h‚āô]` replaces a goal of the form `s ‚ąą f` and terms
`h‚āĀ : t‚āĀ ‚ąą f, ‚čĮ, h‚āô : t‚āô ‚ąą f` with `‚ąÄ x, x ‚ąą t‚āĀ ‚Üí ‚čĮ ‚Üí x ‚ąą t‚āô ‚Üí x ‚ąą s`.
The list is an optional parameter, `[]` being its default value.

`filter_upwards [h‚āĀ, ‚čĮ, h‚āô] with a‚āĀ a‚āā ‚čĮ a‚āĖ` is a short form for
`{ filter_upwards [h‚āĀ, ‚čĮ, h‚āô], intro a‚āĀ a‚āā ‚čĮ a‚āĖ }`.

`filter_upwards [h‚āĀ, ‚čĮ, h‚āô] using e` is a short form for
`{ filter_upwards [h1, ‚čĮ, hn], exact e }`.

Combining both shortcuts is done by writing `filter_upwards [h‚āĀ, ‚čĮ, h‚āô] with a‚āĀ a‚āā ‚čĮ a‚āĖ using e`.
Note that in this case, the `aŠĶĘ` terms can be used in `e`.
-/

example [TopologicalSpace őĪ] {x : őĪ} {p p' q q' : őĪ ‚Üí Prop}
    (hT : {x | p x} ‚ąą ūĚďĚ x)
    (hT' : {x | p' x} ‚ąą ūĚďĚ x)
    (hS : {x | q x} ‚ąą ūĚďĚ x)
    (hS' : {x | q' x} ‚ąą ūĚďĚ x) :
    {x | p x ‚ąß q x ‚ą® p' x ‚ąß q' x} ‚ąą ūĚďĚ x := by
  -- We need to show that {x | p x ‚ąß q x ‚ą® p' x ‚ąß q' x} ‚ąą ūĚďĚ x
  -- We know:
  -- hT : {x | p x} ‚ąą ūĚďĚ x
  -- hT' : {x | p' x} ‚ąą ūĚďĚ x
  -- hS : {x | q x} ‚ąą ūĚďĚ x
  -- hS' : {x | q' x} ‚ąą ūĚďĚ x
  -- The set we want is the union of two sets:
  -- A = {x | p x ‚ąß q x} (intersection of {x | p x} and {x | q x})
  -- B = {x | p' x ‚ąß q' x} (intersection of {x | p' x} and {x | q' x})
  -- Since {x | p x} and {x | q x} are in ūĚďĚ x, their intersection A is in ūĚďĚ x
  -- Since {x | p' x} and {x | q' x} are in ūĚďĚ x, their intersection B is in ūĚďĚ x
  -- Since A and B are in ūĚďĚ x, their union is in ūĚďĚ x
  -- So {x | p x ‚ąß q x ‚ą® p' x ‚ąß q' x} ‚ąą ūĚďĚ x
  -- Let's use filter_upwards to prove this
  -- First, prove that {x | p x ‚ąß q x} ‚ąą ūĚďĚ x
  have h1 : {x | p x ‚ąß q x} ‚ąą ūĚďĚ x := by
    -- {x | p x ‚ąß q x} is the intersection of {x | p x} and {x | q x}
    -- Both are in ūĚďĚ x, so their intersection is in ūĚďĚ x
    exact Filter.mem_inter hT hS

