Now we need to prove this. The definition of $F \leq G$ is that for all sets $s$, $s \in G \implies s \cap F \neq \emptyset$. The definition of $F.map\ f \leq G.map\ f$ is that for all sets $s$, $s \in G.map\ f \implies s \cap F.map\ f \neq \emptyset$.

Let's think about how to prove this. If $s \in G.map\ f$, then there is some set $t \in G$ such that $f(t) \subseteq s$. Since $F \leq G$ and $t \in G$, we have $t \cap F \neq \emptyset$. So there is some point $x \in t \cap F$. Then $f(x) \in f(t) \subseteq s$, and $f(x) \in F.map\ f$. So $f(x) \in s \cap F.map\ f$.

